sorted() Method in Java Stream API

sorted() is an intermediate operation that sorts elements in a stream.

👉 It returns a new stream with elements arranged in a specific order.

First Version of sorted()
Method Signature
Stream<T> sorted()

👉 Uses the natural ordering of elements.

Example with Numbers
List<Integer> numbers =
        List.of(5, 2, 8, 1, 3);

numbers.stream()
       .sorted()
       .forEach(System.out::println);

Output:

1
2
3
5
8
Example with Strings
List<String> fruits =
        List.of("Orange",
                "Apple",
                "Banana");

fruits.stream()
       .sorted()
       .forEach(System.out::println);

Output:

Apple
Banana
Orange
How Does sorted() Work?

For the version without parameters:

.sorted()

Java expects elements to implement:

Comparable<T>

because it needs a way to compare objects.

Custom Objects

Example:

class Person implements Comparable<Person> {

    private String name;

    @Override
    public int compareTo(Person other) {
        return this.name.compareTo(other.name);
    }
}

Now:

people.stream()
      .sorted()
      .forEach(System.out::println);

works correctly.

Second Version of sorted()
Method Signature
Stream<T> sorted(
        Comparator<? super T> comparator
)

👉 Uses a custom sorting rule.

Example: Reverse Order
numbers.stream()
       .sorted((a, b) -> b - a)
       .forEach(System.out::println);

Output:

8
5
3
2
1
Using Comparator Methods
Ascending
people.stream()
      .sorted(
          Comparator.comparing(
              Person::getAge
          )
      );
Descending
people.stream()
      .sorted(
          Comparator.comparing(
              Person::getAge
          ).reversed()
      );
Sorting by Multiple Fields
people.stream()
      .sorted(
          Comparator.comparing(
              Person::getLastName
          )
          .thenComparing(
              Person::getFirstName
          )
      );

👉 First sort by last name.

👉 If equal, sort by first name.

sorted() Is Intermediate
stream.sorted();

Nothing happens yet.

Execution starts only after a terminal operation:

stream.sorted()
      .forEach(System.out::println);
Original Collection Is Not Modified
List<Integer> numbers =
        List.of(5, 2, 8, 1);
numbers.stream()
       .sorted()
       .toList();

Original list:

[5, 2, 8, 1]

remains unchanged.

Time Complexity

Sorting generally requires:

O(n log n)

where n is the number of elements.

Common Use Cases
Sort Numbers
.sorted()
Sort Strings
.sorted()
Sort Objects
.sorted(
    Comparator.comparing(
        Person::getAge
    )
)
Reverse Order
.sorted(
    Comparator.reverseOrder()
)
